# Peer Review Checklist

<!--
Copy this checklist into your review to stay systematic and thorough.
Check items as you work through them.
-->

## 1. Intent Understanding
- [ ] PR description is clear about what changed and why
- [ ] Linked issues provide context
- [ ] I understand the problem being solved

## 2. Test Review
- [ ] Tests exist and are comprehensive
- [ ] Tests verify the claimed behavior
- [ ] Test coverage is adequate for the changes
- [ ] No missing test scenarios

## 3. Correctness
- [ ] Logic is sound and does what the PR claims
- [ ] No off-by-one errors or type mismatches
- [ ] Assumptions about input are documented
- [ ] Code follows the project's conventions

## 4. Edge Cases
- [ ] Empty input / null values handled
- [ ] Boundary values (min, max, zero) handled
- [ ] Concurrent access / race conditions considered
- [ ] Performance impact on large volumes assessed
- [ ] Timeouts and failures handled

## 5. Security
- [ ] User inputs are validated
- [ ] Auth/authz changes are correctly implemented
- [ ] No secrets or credentials exposed
- [ ] Privilege escalations properly gated
- [ ] External integrations use secure protocols

## 6. Feedback Quality
- [ ] Every comment is specific and actionable
- [ ] Comments explain the *why*, not just the *what*
- [ ] Blocking issues are clearly marked
- [ ] Non-blocking suggestions are phrased as suggestions
- [ ] No vague or unhelpful comments

---

## Final Decision

- [ ] **Approve** — Code is ready to merge
- [ ] **Approve with comments** — Good code, has improvement suggestions
- [ ] **Request Changes** — Code has issues that must be fixed
- [ ] **Comment** — Questions / discussion only

**Summary**: [Brief one-liner about the review]
